# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pulseaudio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] Some of the goals of the ALSA project at its inception were automatic configuration of sound-card hardware and graceful handling of multiple sound devices in a system.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] ALSA is released under GPL-2.0-or-later and LGPL-2.1-or-later.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] On Linux, sound servers, like sndio, PulseAudio, JACK (low-latency professional-grade audio editing and mixing) and PipeWire, and higher-level APIs (e.g., OpenAL, SDL audio, etc.) work on top of ALSA and its sound card device drivers.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] ALSA succeeded the older Linux port of the Open Sound System (OSS).
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] The project to develop ALSA was led by Jaroslav Kysela, and was based on the Linux device driver for the Gravis Ultrasound sound card.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] It started in 1998 and was developed separately from the Linux kernel until it was introduced in the 2.5 development series in 2002 (2.5.4–2.5.5).
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] In the 2.6 version, it replaced the previous system, Open Sound System (OSS), by default (although a backwards-compatibility layer does exist).
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] ALSA has a larger and more complex API than OSS, so it can be more difficult to develop an application that uses ALSA as its sound technology.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] While ALSA may be configured to provide an OSS emulation layer, such functionality is no longer available or is not installed by default in many Linux distributions.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] Besides the sound device drivers, ALSA bundles a user-space library for application developers who want to use driver features through an interface that is higher-level than the interface provided for direct interaction with the kernel drivers.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] Unlike the kernel API, which tries to reflect the capabilities of the hardware directly, ALSA's user-space library presents an abstraction that remains as standardized as possible across disparate underlying hardware elements.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] This goal is achieved in part by using software plug-ins; for example, many modern sound cards or built-in sound chips do not have a "master volume" control.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] Instead, for these devices, the user space library provides a software volume control using the "softvol" plug-in, and ordinary application software need not care whether such a control is implemented by underlying hardware or software emulation of such underlying hardware.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] Additional to the software framework internal to the Linux kernel, the ALSA project also provides the command-line tools and utilities `alsactl`, `amixer`, `arecord/aplay` and `alsamixer`, an ncurses-based TUI.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] There also are GUIs programmed by third-party developers, such as GNOME-ALSAmixer (using GTK), Kmix, XFCE4-mixer, LXpanel, QasHctl, QasMixer, Pavucontrol, AconnectGUI, tapiir, polarbear, ALSAmixerGUI (using FLTK), ZynAddSubFX, Yoshimi, and even more.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] Typically, ALSA supports up to eight *cards*, numbered 0 through 7; each card is a physical or logical kernel device capable of input and output.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] Furthermore, each card may also be addressed by its *id*, which is an explanatory string such as "*Headset*" or "*ICH9*".
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] A card has *devices*, numbered starting at 0; a device may be of *playback* type, meaning it outputs sound from the computer, or some other type such as *capture*, *control*, *timer*, or *sequencer*; device number 0 is used by default when no particular device is specified.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] A device may have *subdevices*, numbered starting at 0; a subdevice represents some relevant sound endpoint for the device, such as a speaker pair.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] If the subdevice is not specified, or if subdevice number −1 is specified, then any available subdevice is used.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] A card's *interface* is a description of an ALSA protocol for accessing the card; possible interfaces include: *hw*, *plughw*, *default*, and *plug:dmix*.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] The *hw* interface provides direct access to the kernel device, but no software mixing or stream adaptation support.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] The *plughw* and *default* enable sound output where the *hw* interface would produce an error.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] The ALSA System on Chip (ASoC) layer aims to provide better support for ALSA on embedded systems that use a system-on-chip (SoC) design.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] Open Sound System version 4 is able to emulate ALSA.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] QNX uses a sound system derived from, but not directly compatible with ALSA.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] The header file and library names are still "asound", same as the ALSA names.
[src:pulseaudio/advanced-linux-sound-architecture] ALSA API uses ioctl() calls in a way not allowed in the QNX kernel.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] In a digital audio system, an analog electrical signal representing the sound is converted with an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) into a digital signal, typically using pulse-code modulation (PCM).
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] This digital signal can then be recorded, edited, modified, and copied using computers, audio playback machines, and other digital tools.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] For playback, a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) performs the reverse process, converting a digital signal back into an analog signal, which is then sent through an audio power amplifier and ultimately to a loudspeaker.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio systems may include compression, storage, processing, and transmission components.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Conversion to a digital format allows convenient manipulation, storage, transmission, and retrieval of an audio signal.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Unlike analog audio, in which making copies of a recording results in generation loss and degradation of signal quality, digital audio allows an infinite number of copies to be made without any degradation of signal quality.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio technologies are used in the recording, manipulation, mass-production, and distribution of sound, including recordings of songs, instrumental pieces, podcasts, sound effects, and other sounds.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Modern online music distribution depends on digital recording and data compression.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The availability of music as data files, rather than as physical objects, has significantly reduced the costs of distribution as well as making it easier to share copies.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Before digital audio, the music industry distributed and sold music by selling physical copies in the form of records and cassette tapes.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] With digital audio and online distribution systems such as iTunes, companies sell digital sound files to consumers, which the consumer receives over the Internet.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Popular streaming services such as Apple Music, Spotify, or YouTube, offer temporary access to the digital file, and are now the most common form of music consumption.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] An analog audio system converts physical waveforms of sound into electrical representations of those waveforms by use of a transducer, such as a microphone.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The sounds are then stored on an analog medium such as magnetic tape, or transmitted through an analog medium such as a telephone line or radio.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The process is reversed for reproduction: the electrical audio signal is amplified and then converted back into physical waveforms via a loudspeaker.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Analog audio retains its fundamental wave-like characteristics throughout its storage, transformation, duplication, and amplification.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Analog audio signals are susceptible to noise and distortion, due to the innate characteristics of electronic circuits and associated devices.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Disturbances in a digital system do not result in error unless they are so large as to result in a symbol being misinterpreted as another symbol or disturbing the sequence of symbols.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] It is, therefore, generally possible to have an entirely error-free digital audio system in which no noise or distortion is introduced between conversion to digital format and conversion back to analog.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] A digital audio signal may be encoded for correction of any errors that might occur in the storage or transmission of the signal.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] This technique, known as channel coding, is essential for broadcast or recorded digital systems to maintain bit accuracy.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Eight-to-fourteen modulation is the channel code used for the audio compact disc (CD).
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] If an audio signal is analog, a digital audio system starts with an ADC that converts an analog signal to a digital signal.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The ADC runs at a specified sampling rate and converts at a known bit resolution.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] CD audio, for example, has a sampling rate of 44.1 kHz (44,100 samples per second), and has 16-bit resolution for each stereo channel.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Analog signals that have not already been bandlimited must be passed through an anti-aliasing filter before conversion, to prevent the aliasing distortion that is caused by audio signals with frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency (half the sampling rate).
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] A digital audio signal may be stored or transmitted.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio can be stored on a CD, a digital audio player, a hard drive, a USB flash drive, or any other digital data storage device.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The digital signal may be altered through digital signal processing, where it may be filtered or have effects applied.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Sample-rate conversion, including upsampling and downsampling, may be used to change signals that have been encoded with a different sampling rate to a common sampling rate prior to processing.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Audio data compression techniques, such as MP3, Advanced Audio Coding (AAC), Opus, Ogg Vorbis, or FLAC, are commonly employed to reduce the file size.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio can be carried over digital audio interfaces such as AES3 or MADI.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio can be carried over a network using audio over Ethernet, audio over IP or other streaming media standards and systems.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] For playback, digital audio must be converted back to an analog signal with a DAC.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] According to the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, with some practical and theoretical restrictions, a band-limited version of the original analog signal can be accurately reconstructed from the digital signal.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] During conversion, audio data can be embedded with a digital watermark to prevent piracy and unauthorized use.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Watermarking is done using a direct-sequence spread-spectrum (DSSS) method.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The audio information is then modulated by a pseudo-noise (PN) sequence, then shaped within the frequency domain and put back in the original signal.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The strength of the embedding determines the strength of the watermark on the audio data.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Pulse-code modulation (PCM) was invented by British scientist Alec Reeves in 1937.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Chapin Cutler of Bell Labs filed the patent on differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM), a data compression algorithm.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) was introduced by P.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression, with linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Initial concepts for LPC date back to the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Schroeder at Bell Labs developed a form of LPC called adaptive predictive coding (APC), a perceptual coding algorithm that exploited the masking properties of the human ear, followed in the early 1980s with the code-excited linear prediction (CELP) algorithm.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Discrete cosine transform (DCT) coding, a lossy compression method first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, provided the basis for the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), which was developed by J.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The MDCT is the basis for most audio coding standards, such as Dolby Digital (AC-3), MP3 (MPEG Layer III), AAC, Windows Media Audio (WMA), Opus and Vorbis (Ogg).
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] PCM was used in telecommunications applications long before its first use in commercial broadcast and recording.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Commercial digital recording was pioneered in Japan by NHK and Nippon Columbia and their Denon brand, in the 1960s.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The first commercial digital recordings were released in 1971.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The BBC also began to experiment with digital audio in the 1960s.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] By the early 1970s, it had developed a 2-channel recorder, and in 1972 it deployed a digital audio transmission system that linked its broadcast center to its remote transmitters.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The first 16-bit PCM recording in the United States was made by Thomas Stockham at the Santa Fe Opera in 1976, on a Soundstream recorder.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] An improved version of the Soundstream system was used to produce several classical recordings by Telarc in 1978.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The 3M digital multitrack recorder in development at the time was based on BBC technology.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The first all-digital album recorded on this machine was Ry Cooder's *Bop till You Drop* in 1979.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] British record label Decca began development of its own 2-track digital audio recorders in 1978 and released the first European digital recording in 1979.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Popular professional digital multitrack recorders produced by Sony/Studer (DASH) and Mitsubishi (ProDigi) in the early 1980s helped to bring about digital recording's acceptance by the major record companies.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Machines for these formats had their own transports built in as well, using reel-to-reel tape in either 1/4, 1/2, or 1-inch widths, with the audio data being recorded to the tape using a multi-track stationary tape head.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] PCM adaptors allowed for stereo digital audio recording on a conventional NTSC or PAL video tape recorder.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The 1982 introduction of the CD by Philips and Sony popularized digital audio with consumers.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] ADAT became available in the early 1990s, which allowed eight-track 44.1 or 48 kHz recording on S-VHS cassettes, and DTRS performed a similar function with Hi8 tapes.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Like the DAT cassette, ProDigi and DASH machines also accommodated the obligatory 44.1 kHz sampling rate, but also 48 kHz on all machines, and eventually a 96 kHz sampling rate.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Unlike analog systems, modern digital audio workstations and audio interfaces allow as many channels in as many different sampling rates as the computer can effectively run at a single time.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Avid Audio and Steinberg released the first digital audio workstation software programs in 1989.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio workstations make multitrack recording and mixing much easier for large projects, which would otherwise be difficult with analog equipment.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The rapid development and wide adoption of PCM digital telephony was enabled by metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) switched capacitor (SC) circuit technology, developed in the early 1970s.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] This led to the development of PCM codec-filter chips in the late 1970s.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] The silicon-gate CMOS (complementary MOS) PCM codec-filter chip, developed by David A.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Black in 1980, has since been the industry standard for digital telephony.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio is used in broadcasting of audio.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Standard technologies include Digital audio broadcasting (DAB), Digital Radio Mondiale (DRM), HD Radio and In-band on-channel (IBOC).
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio in recording applications is stored on audio-specific technologies including CD, DAT, Digital Compact Cassette (DCC) and MiniDisc.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio may be stored in a standard audio file formats and stored on a Hard disk recorder, Blu-ray or DVD-Audio.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Files may be played back on smartphones, computers or MP3 player.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Digital audio resolution is measured in audio bit depth.
[src:pulseaudio/digital-audio] Most digital audio formats use either 16-bit, 24-bit, and 32-bit resolution.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Latency can be a critical performance metric in professional audio, including sound reinforcement systems, foldback systems (especially those using in-ear monitors) live radio and television.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Excessive audio latency has the potential to degrade call quality in telecommunications applications.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Low-latency audio in computers is important for interactivity.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] In all systems, latency can be said to consist of three elements: codec delay, playout delay and network delay.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Latency in telephone calls is sometimes referred to as **mouth-to-ear delay**; the telecommunications industry also uses the term *quality of experience* (QoE).
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Voice quality is measured according to the ITU model; measurable quality of a call degrades rapidly where the mouth-to-ear delay latency exceeds 200 milliseconds.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] The mean opinion score (MOS) is also comparable in a near-linear fashion with the ITU's quality scale - defined in standards G.107, G.108 and G.109 - with a quality factor *R* ranging from 0 to 100.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] An MOS of 4 ('Good') would have an *R* score of 80 or above; to achieve 100R requires an MOS exceeding 4.5.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Similarly, the G.114 recommendation regarding mouth-to-ear delay indicates that most users are "very satisfied" as long as latency does not exceed 200 ms, with an according *R* of 90+.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Codec choice also plays an important role; the highest quality (and highest bandwidth) codecs like G.711 are usually configured to incur the least encode-decode latency, so on a network with sufficient throughput sub-100 ms latencies can be achieved.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] G.711 at a bitrate of 64 kbit/s is the encoding method predominantly used on the public switched telephone network.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] The AMR narrowband codec, used in GSM and UMTS networks, introduces latency in the encode and decode processes.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] With end-to-end QoS managed and assured rate connections, latency can be reduced to analogue PSTN/POTS levels.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] On a stable connection with sufficient bandwidth and minimal latency, VoIP systems typically have a minimum of 20 ms inherent latency.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Under less ideal network conditions a 150 ms maximum latency is sought for general consumer use.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Many popular videoconferencing systems rely on data buffering and data redundancy to cope for network jitter and packet loss.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Measurements have shown that mouth-to-ear delay are between 160 and 300 ms over a 500-mile distance, on average US network conditions.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Latency is a larger consideration when an echo is present and systems must perform echo suppression and cancellation.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Latency can be a particular problem in audio platforms on computers.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Supported interface optimizations reduce the delay to times that are too short for the human ear to detect.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] By reducing buffer sizes, latency can be reduced.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] A popular optimization solution is Steinberg's ASIO, which bypasses the audio platform and connects audio signals directly to the sound card's hardware.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Many professional and semi-professional audio applications utilize the ASIO driver, allowing users to work with audio in real time.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Pro Tools HD offers a low-latency system similar to ASIO.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Pro Tools 10 and 11 are also compatible with ASIO interface drivers.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] The Linux real-time kernel is a modified kernel that alters the standard timer frequency the Linux kernel uses and gives all processes or threads the ability to have real-time priority.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] This means that a time-critical process like an audio stream can get priority over another, less-critical process like network activity.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] This is also configurable per user (for example, the processes of user "tux" could have priority over processes of user "nobody" or over the processes of several system daemons).
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Many modern digital television receivers, set-top boxes and AV receivers use sophisticated audio processing, which can create a delay between the time when the audio signal is received and the time when it is heard on the speakers.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Since TVs also introduce delays in processing the video signal, this can result in the two signals being sufficiently synchronized to be unnoticeable by the viewer.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] However, if the difference between the audio and video delay is significant, the effect can be disconcerting.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Some systems have a lip sync setting that allows the audio lag to be adjusted to synchronize with the video, and others may have advanced settings where some of the audio processing steps can be turned off.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Audio lag is also a significant detriment in rhythm games, where precise timing is required to succeed.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Most of these games have a lag calibration setting whereby the game will adjust the timing windows by a certain number of milliseconds to compensate.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] In these cases, the notes of a song will be sent to the speakers before the game even receives the required input from the player in order to maintain the illusion of rhythm.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Games that rely upon musical improvisation, such as Rock Band drums or DJ Hero, can still suffer tremendously, as the game cannot predict what the player will hit in these cases, and excessive lag will still create a noticeable delay between hitting notes and hearing them play.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Audio latency can be experienced in broadcast systems where someone is contributing to a live broadcast over a satellite or similar link with high delay.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] The person in the main studio has to wait for the contributor at the other end of the link to react to questions.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Latency in this context could be between several hundred milliseconds and a few seconds.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Dealing with audio latencies as high as this takes special training in order to make the resulting combined audio output reasonably acceptable to the listeners.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Wherever practical, it is important to try to keep live production audio latency low in order to keep the reactions and interchange of participants as natural as possible.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] A latency of 10 milliseconds or better is the target for audio circuits within professional production structures.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Latency in live performance occurs naturally from the speed of sound.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] It takes sound about 3 milliseconds to travel 1 meter.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Small amounts of latency occur between performers, depending on how they are spaced from each other and from stage monitors if these are used.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] This creates a practical limit to how far apart the artists in a group can be from one another.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Stage monitoring extends that limit, as sound in the form of an electrical signal travels close to the speed of light through the cables that connect stage monitors.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Performers, particularly in large spaces, will also hear reverberation, or echo of their music, as the sound that projects from the stage, bounces off of walls and structures, and returns with latency and distortion.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] A primary purpose of stage monitoring is to provide artists with more primary sound so that they are not confused by the latency of these reverberations.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] While analog audio equipment has no appreciable latency, digital audio equipment has latency associated with two general processes: conversion from one format to another, and digital signal processing (DSP) tasks such as equalization, compression and routing.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Digital conversion processes include analog-to-digital converters (ADC), digital-to-analog converters (DAC), and various changes from one digital format to another, such as AES3 which carries low-voltage electrical signals to ADAT, an optical transport.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Any such process takes a small amount of time to accomplish; typical latencies are in the range of 0.2 to 1.5 milliseconds, depending on sampling rate, software design and hardware architecture.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Different audio signal processing operations, such as finite impulse response (FIR) and infinite impulse response (IIR) filters, take different mathematical approaches to the same end and can have different latencies.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] In addition, input and output sample buffering add delay.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Typical latencies range from 0.5 to 10 milliseconds, with some designs having as much as 30 milliseconds of delay.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Latency in digital audio equipment is most noticeable when a singer's voice is transmitted through their microphone, through digital audio mixing, processing and routing paths, then sent to their own ears via in-ear monitors or headphones.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] In this case, the singer's vocal sound is conducted to their own ear through the bones of the head, then through the digital pathway to their ears some milliseconds later.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] In one study, listeners found latency greater than 15 ms to be noticeable.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Latency for other musical activities, such as playing guitar, does not have the same critical concern.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Ten milliseconds of latency isn't as noticeable to a listener who is not hearing his or her own voice.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] In sound reinforcement for music or speech presentation in large venues, it is optimal to deliver sufficient sound volume to the back of the venue without resorting to excessive sound volumes near the front.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] One way for audio engineers to achieve this is to use additional loudspeakers placed at a distance from the stage but closer to the rear of the audience.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Sound travels through air at the speed of sound (around 343 metres (1,125 ft) per second depending on air temperature and humidity).
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] Because of the Haas effect an *additional* 15 milliseconds can be added to the delay time of the loudspeakers nearer the audience, so that the stage's wavefront reaches them first, to focus the audience's attention on the stage rather than the local loudspeaker.
[src:pulseaudio/latency-audio] The slightly later sound from delayed loudspeakers simply increases the perceived sound level without negatively affecting localization.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] The **Open Sound System** (OSS) is an interface for making and capturing sound in Unix and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] It is based on standard Unix devices system calls (i.e.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] The term also sometimes refers to the software in a Unix kernel that provides the OSS interface; it can be thought of as a device driver (or a collection of device drivers) for sound controller hardware.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] The goal of OSS is to allow the writing of sound-based applications that are agnostic of the underlying sound hardware.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] OSS was created by Hannu Savolainen and is distributed under four license options, three of which are free software licences, thus making OSS free software.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] The API is designed to use the traditional Unix framework of open(), read(), write(), and ioctl(), via device files.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] For instance, the default device for sound input and output is **/dev/dsp**.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] OSS implements the /dev/audio interface.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] Detailed access to individual sound devices is provided via the /dev/oss directory.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] OSS also has MIDI support in /dev/sequencer, /dev/music (both legacy) and /dev/mini.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] On Linux, OSS4 is also able to emulate ALSA, its open-source replacement.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] OSS was originally "VoxWare", a Linux kernel sound driver by Hannu Savolainen.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] Savolainen made the code available under free software licenses, GPL for Linux and BSD for BSD distributions.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] Between November 1993 (and Linux 1.00) and 1997, OSS was the sole choice of sound system in FreeBSD and Linux.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] This was changed when Luigi Rizzo wrote a new "pcm" driver for FreeBSD in 1997, and when Jaroslav Kysela started Advanced Linux Sound Architecture in 1998.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] In 2002, Savolainen was contracted by the company 4Front Technologies and made the upcoming OSS 4, which includes support for newer sound devices and improvements, proprietary.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] In response, the Linux community abandoned the OSS/free implementation included in the kernel and development effort switched to the replacement Advanced Linux Sound Architecture (ALSA).
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] FreeBSD by this time had switched to a "newpcm" project started in 1999 and was not affected.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] In July 2007, 4Front Technologies released sources for OSS under CDDL-1.0 for OpenSolaris and GPL-2.0-only for Linux.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] Drivers for some soundcards remained closed-source and were not included in the release.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] In January 2008, 4Front Technologies released OSS for FreeBSD (and other BSD systems) under the BSD-2-Clause.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] OSS4 now exists mostly as a standalone piece of software, not integrated into the kernel source code.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] The exception is Solaris and OpenSolaris, which use a fork of OSS4 called Boomer.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] It combines the OSS4 framework (audio and mixer) together with Sun's earlier SADA (/dev/audio) API.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] Although Linux distributions such as Ubuntu made OSS4 available as a software package after it was made free software, they have chosen to ignore any bugs filed against these packages.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] The OSS API has remained influential despite the obscurity of the original library.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] NetBSD's documentation describes it as "the preferred API in FreeBSD and Solaris".
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] FreeBSD contains an independently developed implementation of the OSS API, which includes, among other things, in-kernel resampling, mixing (vchans), equalizer, surround sound, and independent volume control for each application.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] It gradually evolved from the "newpcm" replacement written in 1999 and caught up with OSS4 API around 2005.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] NetBSD supports a compatibility mode for the OSS API, by providing the `soundcard.h` header file and the `libossaudio` library, which internally operate using the native Sun-like audio interface.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] The replacement was first seen in NetBSD 1.3 of 1998.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] Linux had, as aforementioned, switched to Advanced Linux Sound Architecture since 2003 (kernel 2.6).
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] ALSA provides an optional, in-kernel, OSS emulation mode that appears to programs as if it were OSS.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] ALSA also has a *aoss* userspace program that works by intercepting systems calls directed to the OSS device files.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] OSS/3D is a plugin for music players, which acts as an audio postprocessing engine.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] Supported players include Winamp, Windows Media Player (9 or later), musicmatch, Sonique, Foobar2000, JetAudio, XMMS.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] It is ported to Windows and Linux platforms.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] 4Front OSS3D was later renamed to Joesoft Hear.
[src:pulseaudio/open-sound-system] OSS both as API and as software has been criticized by some developers, such as Paul Davis (of JACK Audio Connection Kit) and Lennart Poettering (of competing PulseAudio).
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] PulseAudio is free and open-source software, and is licensed under the terms of the LGPL-2.1-or-later.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] It was created in 2004 under the name Polypaudio but was renamed in 2006 to PulseAudio.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] PulseAudio competes with newer PipeWire, which provides a compatible PulseAudio server (known as pipewire-pulse), and PipeWire is now used by default on many Linux distributions, including Fedora Linux, Ubuntu, and Debian.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] On Microsoft Windows, PulseAudio runs in Windows Subsystem for Linux.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] The NT kernel was previously supported via MinGW (an implementation of the GNU toolchain, which includes various tools such as GCC and binutils).
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] The NT kernel port has not been updated since 2011, however.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] In broad terms ALSA is a kernel subsystem that provides the sound hardware driver, and PulseAudio is the interface engine between applications and ALSA.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] However, its use is not mandatory and audio can still be played and mixed together without PulseAudio.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] PulseAudio acts as a sound server, where a background process accepting sound input from one or more *sources* (processes, capture devices, etc.) is created.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] The background process then redirects these sound sources to one or more *sinks* (sound cards, remote network PulseAudio servers, or other processes).
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] One of the goals of PulseAudio is to reroute all sound streams through it, including those from processes that attempt to directly access the hardware (like legacy OSS applications).
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] PulseAudio achieves this by providing adapters to applications using other audio systems, like aRts and ESD.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] In a typical installation scenario under Linux, the user configures ALSA to use a virtual device provided by PulseAudio.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] Thus, applications using ALSA will output sound to PulseAudio, which then uses ALSA itself to access the real sound card.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] PulseAudio also provides its own native interface to applications that want to support PulseAudio directly, as well as a legacy interface for ESD applications, making it suitable as a drop-in replacement for ESD.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] For OSS applications, PulseAudio provides the `padsp` utility, which replaces device files such as `/dev/dsp`, tricking the applications into believing that they have exclusive control over the sound card.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] In reality, their output is rerouted through PulseAudio.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] libSydney is a total replacement for the "PulseAudio streaming API", and plans have been made for libSydney to eventually become the only audio API used in PulseAudio.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] PulseAudio first appeared for regular users in Fedora Linux, starting with version 8, then was adopted by major Linux distributions such as Ubuntu, Debian, Mandriva Linux, and openSUSE.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] There is support for PulseAudio in the GNOME project, and also in KDE, as it is integrated into Plasma Workspaces, adding support to Phonon (the KDE multimedia framework) and KMix (the integrated mixer application) as well as a "Speaker Setup" GUI to aid the configuration of multi-channel speakers.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] PulseAudio is also available in the Illumos distribution OpenIndiana, and enabled by default in its MATE desktop environment.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] Various Linux-based mobile devices, including Nokia N900, Nokia N9 and the Palm Pre use PulseAudio.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] Tizen, an open-source mobile operating system, which is a project of the Linux Foundation and is governed by a Technical Steering Group (TSG) composed of Intel and Samsung, uses PulseAudio.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] JACK is a sound server that provides real-time, low-latency (i.e.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] 5 milliseconds or less) audio performance and, since JACK2, supports efficient load balancing by utilizing symmetric multiprocessing; that is, the load of all audio clients can be distributed among several processors.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] JACK is the preferred sound server for professional audio applications such as Ardour, ReZound, and LinuxSampler; multiple free audio-production distributions use it as the default audio server.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] It is possible for JACK and PulseAudio to coexist: while JACK is running, PulseAudio can automatically connect itself as a JACK client, allowing PulseAudio clients to make and record sound at the same time as JACK clients.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] PipeWire is an audio and video server that "aims to support the use cases currently handled by both PulseAudio and Jack".
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] Before JACK and PulseAudio, sound on these systems was managed by multi-purpose integrated audio solutions.
[src:pulseaudio/pulseaudio] These solutions do not fully cover the mixing and sound streaming process, but they are still used by JACK and PulseAudio to send the final audio stream to the sound card.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] A **sound server** is software that manages the use of and access to audio devices (usually a sound card).
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] It commonly runs as a background process.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] In a Unix-like operating system, a sound server mixes different data streams (usually raw PCM audio) and sends out a single unified audio to an output device.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] The mixing is usually done by software, or by hardware if there is a supported sound card.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] Sound servers appeared in Unix-like operating systems after limitations in Open Sound System were recognized.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] OSS is a basic sound interface that was incapable of playing multiple streams simultaneously, dealing with multiple sound cards, or streaming sound over the network.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] A sound server can provide these features by running as a daemon.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] It receives calls from different programs and sound flows, mixes the streams, and sends raw audio out to the audio device.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] With a sound server, users can also configure global and per-application sound preferences.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] As of 2012 there are multiple sound servers; some focus on providing very low latency, while others concentrate on features suitable for general desktop systems.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] While diversification allows a user to choose just the features that are important to a particular application, it also forces developers to accommodate these options by necessitating code that is compatible with the various sound servers available.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] Consequently, this variety has resulted in a desire for a standard API to unify efforts.
[src:pulseaudio/sound-server] In 2017, PipeWire began incorporating audio support, and would then go on to realize that unification for the most part.
